  {
    "id": 10,
    "title": "Work order, QA document and Rejection Reporting",
    "description": "Work order, QA document and Rejection Reporting",
    "video_url": "http://localhost:8000/static/videos/2500fb60-8936-408a-a174-b3008dd29fc6.mp4",
    "created_by_id": 1,
    "objectives": "## Objectives\n- Understand the process of creating a work order based on customer drawings and specifications\n- Learn how to identify and document key parameters such as material, wire dye, ID, number of turns, and length in a work order\n- Familiarize oneself with the in-process inspection procedure, including verification of dimensions and detection of non-conformities\n- Understand the process of holding and reworking non-conforming products, including the use of red tags and scrap notes\n- Learn how to document and report non-conformities, including the use of specific formats and details such as work order numbers, batch numbers, and customer information",
    "applications": "## Definitions\n- **Work Order**: A document that outlines the specifications and requirements for a particular job or project, including customer specifications and parameters.\n- **Customer Specification**: A document that outlines the requirements and parameters for a particular product or service, as specified by the customer.\n- **In-Process Inspection**: The process of inspecting and verifying the quality of a product during its production, to ensure that it meets the required specifications and standards.\n- **Non-Conformity**: A deviation from the specified requirements or standards, which can result in a product being rejected or requiring rework.\n- **Rework**: The process of correcting or repairing a product that has been found to be non-conforming, to bring it back into specification.\n- **Scrap**: Materials or products that are rejected or discarded due to non-conformity or other defects.\n\n## Practical Application\n- Creating a work order based on customer specifications and parameters, such as metal type, wire diameter, inner diameter, number of turns, and length.\n- Conducting in-process inspections at regular intervals (e.g. every 2 hours) to verify that the product meets the required specifications.\n- Identifying and addressing non-conformities, such as out-of-spec dimensions or defects, and taking corrective action to rework or scrap the product.\n- Using tools and techniques, such as measurement and testing equipment, to verify the quality and specifications of the product.\n- Maintaining accurate records and documentation, such as work orders, inspection reports, and scrap reports, to track production and quality control.\n- Implementing a quality control process that includes inspection, testing, and verification of products to ensure that they meet customer specifications and requirements.\n- Using a red tag system to identify and segregate non-conforming products, and to track and report scrap materials.\n- Collaborating with production teams, quality control teams, and customers to ensure that products meet specifications and requirements, and to address any non-conformities or defects.",
    "quiz_data": "[{\"question\":\"What is the primary purpose of a work order?\",\"options\":[\"A) To track customer complaints\",\"B) To outline the production process and customer specifications\",\"C) To monitor employee performance\",\"D) To manage inventory levels\"],\"correct_answer\":\"B) To outline the production process and customer specifications\",\"explanation\":\"A work order is used to outline the production process and customer specifications, ensuring that the final product meets the required standards.\"},{\"question\":\"What information is typically included in a work order?\",\"options\":[\"A) Only the customer's name and order number\",\"B) The customer's drawing, material specifications, and production requirements\",\"C) The production schedule and employee assignments\",\"D) The quality control procedures and inspection schedules\"],\"correct_answer\":\"B) The customer's drawing, material specifications, and production requirements\",\"explanation\":\"A work order typically includes the customer's drawing, material specifications, and production requirements to ensure that the final product meets the customer's needs.\"},{\"question\":\"What is the purpose of in-process inspection?\",\"options\":[\"A) To identify defects in the final product\",\"B) To monitor the production process and ensure that it meets customer specifications\",\"C) To train new employees on production procedures\",\"D) To conduct quality control audits\"],\"correct_answer\":\"B) To monitor the production process and ensure that it meets customer specifications\",\"explanation\":\"In-process inspection is used to monitor the production process and ensure that it meets customer specifications, allowing for prompt identification and correction of any deviations.\"},{\"question\":\"What happens to a product that fails to meet customer specifications during in-process inspection?\",\"options\":[\"A) It is shipped to the customer with a warning label\",\"B) It is reworked to meet the customer's specifications\",\"C) It is placed on hold and may be reworked or scrapped\",\"D) It is immediately scrapped and disposed of\"],\"correct_answer\":\"C) It is placed on hold and may be reworked or scrapped\",\"explanation\":\"If a product fails to meet customer specifications during in-process inspection, it is typically placed on hold and may be reworked or scrapped, depending on the nature of the defect.\"},{\"question\":\"What is the purpose of a rejection report?\",\"options\":[\"A) To document employee errors and performance issues\",\"B) To track customer complaints and feedback\",\"C) To record and report on products that do not meet customer specifications\",\"D) To monitor inventory levels and track product shipments\"],\"correct_answer\":\"C) To record and report on products that do not meet customer specifications\",\"explanation\":\"A rejection report is used to record and report on products that do not meet customer specifications, providing a formal documentation of the defect and the actions taken to address it.\"},{\"question\":\"What information is typically included in a rejection report?\",\"options\":[\"A) Only the product description and quantity\",\"B) The product description, quantity, reason for rejection, and customer information\",\"C) The production schedule and employee assignments\",\"D) The quality control procedures and inspection schedules\"],\"correct_answer\":\"B) The product description, quantity, reason for rejection, and customer information\",\"explanation\":\"A rejection report typically includes the product description, quantity, reason for rejection, and customer information, providing a detailed record of the rejected product and the actions taken.\"},{\"question\":\"What is the purpose of a red tag in the context of rejection reporting?\",\"options\":[\"A) To identify products that are ready for shipment\",\"B) To mark products that are on hold for rework or inspection\",\"C) To label products that are rejected and cannot be reworked\",\"D) To track inventory levels and monitor product movement\"],\"correct_answer\":\"C) To label products that are rejected and cannot be reworked\",\"explanation\":\"A red tag is used to label products that are rejected and cannot be reworked, providing a clear indication that the product is defective and cannot be used or sold.\"},{\"question\":\"What happens to a product that is tagged with a red tag?\",\"options\":[\"A) It is shipped to the customer with a warning label\",\"B) It is reworked to meet the customer's specifications\",\"C) It is scrapped and disposed of\",\"D) It is placed in storage for future use\"],\"correct_answer\":\"C) It is scrapped and disposed of\",\"explanation\":\"A product that is tagged with a red tag is typically scrapped and disposed of, as it is deemed to be defective and cannot be reworked or used.\"},{\"question\":\"What is the purpose of segregation in the context of rejection reporting?\",\"options\":[\"A) To separate products that are ready for shipment from those that are on hold\",\"B) To isolate defective products from good products\",\"C) To track inventory levels and monitor product movement\",\"D) To conduct quality control audits\"],\"correct_answer\":\"B) To isolate defective products from good products\",\"explanation\":\"Segregation is used to isolate defective products from good products, ensuring that the defective products are not mixed with good products and that the good products are not contaminated or affected by the defective products.\"},{\"question\":\"What is the purpose of a scrap note in the context of rejection reporting?\",\"options\":[\"A) To document employee errors and performance issues\",\"B) To track customer complaints and feedback\",\"C) To record and report on products that are scrapped and disposed of\",\"D) To monitor inventory levels and track product shipments\"],\"correct_answer\":\"C) To record and report on products that are scrapped and disposed of\",\"explanation\":\"A scrap note is used to record and report on products that are scrapped and disposed of, providing a formal documentation of the scrapped product and the reason for its disposal.\"},{\"question\":\"what is the id of given sample A?\",\"type\":\"numerical\",\"options\":[],\"correct_answer\":\"5.33\",\"explanation\":\"Explanation here\",\"tolerance\":0.03}]",
    "is_processing": false
  },
