  {
    "id": 26,
    "title": "Work order, QA document and Rejection Reporting",
    "description": "Work order, QA document and Rejection Reporting",
    "video_url": "http://localhost:8000/static/videos/f903d5f6-3817-4f62-b95b-7102e26dc0e7.mp4",
    "created_by_id": 1,
    "objectives": "## Objectives\n- Understand the process of creating a work order based on customer drawings and specifications\n- Learn how to identify and document key parameters such as metal type, wire dye, ID, number of turns, and length\n- Familiarize yourself with the in-process inspection procedure, including verification of parts at regular intervals and holding production if non-conformities are found\n- Understand the process of rework and scrap management, including segregation, tagging, and documentation of non-conforming parts\n- Learn how to maintain accurate records and documentation throughout the production process, including work orders, inspection records, and scrap reports",
    "applications": "## Definitions\n- **Work Order**: A document that outlines the tasks and specifications required to complete a particular job or project.\n- **Customer Drawing**: A technical drawing provided by the customer that outlines the specifications and requirements of the product.\n- **In-Process Inspection**: The process of inspecting and verifying the product during various stages of production to ensure that it meets the required specifications.\n- **Quality Inspector**: A person responsible for inspecting and verifying the product to ensure that it meets the required specifications.\n- **Hold Card**: A document used to identify and track products that do not meet the required specifications.\n- **Rework**: The process of correcting or repairing products that do not meet the required specifications.\n- **Scrap**: Products that are deemed unusable or defective and are discarded.\n\n## Practical Application\n- Creating a work order based on customer drawings and specifications to ensure that the product meets the required standards.\n- Conducting in-process inspections to verify that the product meets the required specifications during various stages of production.\n- Using hold cards to identify and track products that do not meet the required specifications.\n- Implementing rework processes to correct or repair products that do not meet the required specifications.\n- Maintaining accurate records of production, inspection, and rework to ensure quality control and continuous improvement.\n- Utilizing quality inspectors to verify products and ensure that they meet the required specifications.\n- Implementing a scrap management system to track and dispose of defective or unusable products.\n- Using technical drawings and specifications to guide production and ensure that products meet customer requirements.\n- Conducting regular inspections and audits to ensure that products meet the required standards and specifications.",
    "quiz_data": "[{\"question\": \"What is the primary purpose of including customer specifications in a work order?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) To provide a general overview of the production process\", \"B) To ensure that the final product meets the customer's quality standards\", \"C) To determine the most efficient machine setup for production\", \"D) To establish a baseline for cost estimation\"], \"correct_answer\": \"B) To ensure that the final product meets the customer's quality standards\", \"explanation\": \"Including customer specifications in a work order ensures that the production team understands the exact requirements of the customer, allowing them to produce a final product that meets those standards.\", \"module_index\": 0}, {\"question\": \"How does the production team use the work order to set up their machines?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) By using the work order as a guide to determine the optimal production schedule\", \"B) By referencing the customer specifications outlined in the work order to configure their machines\", \"C) By relying on their own experience and judgment to set up the machines\", \"D) By using a separate machine setup protocol that is not related to the work order\"], \"correct_answer\": \"B) By referencing the customer specifications outlined in the work order to configure their machines\", \"explanation\": \"The work order provides a detailed outline of the customer's specifications, which the production team uses to set up their machines and ensure that the final product meets the required standards.\", \"module_index\": 0}, {\"question\": \"What is the relationship between the work order and the final product's dimensions?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) The work order determines the final product's dimensions, but not the production process\", \"B) The work order outlines the production process, but not the final product's dimensions\", \"C) The work order specifies the customer's required dimensions, which are then used to guide the production process\", \"D) The work order has no direct relationship to the final product's dimensions\"], \"correct_answer\": \"C) The work order specifies the customer's required dimensions, which are then used to guide the production process\", \"explanation\": \"The work order includes the customer's specifications, which outline the required dimensions of the final product. The production team uses this information to guide the production process and ensure that the final product meets the customer's requirements.\", \"module_index\": 0}, {\"question\": \"At what stage of the production process is the work order typically released to the production team?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) After the production team has completed the initial setup of their machines\", \"B) Before the production team begins setting up their machines\", \"C) During the quality inspection phase of the production process\", \"D) After the final product has been completed and inspected\"], \"correct_answer\": \"B) Before the production team begins setting up their machines\", \"explanation\": \"The work order is typically released to the production team before they begin setting up their machines, providing them with the necessary information to configure their machines and produce a final product that meets the customer's specifications.\", \"module_index\": 0}, {\"question\": \"During in-process inspection, what is the primary purpose of verifying the part's specifications every 2 hours?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) To ensure the machine is operating within a 5% tolerance\", \"B) To guarantee the part's dimensions are within a 1% variance\", \"C) To confirm the part meets the specified quality standards\", \"D) To check if the production rate is within a 10% margin of the target\"], \"correct_answer\": \"C) To confirm the part meets the specified quality standards\", \"explanation\": \"The primary purpose of in-process inspection is to ensure the part meets the required quality standards, which involves verifying its specifications at regular intervals.\", \"module_index\": 1}, {\"question\": \"If a quality inspector finds a defective part during verification, what action is taken?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) The part is reworked and returned to production\", \"B) The part is scrapped and a new one is manufactured\", \"C) The production for that hour is put on hold until the issue is resolved\", \"D) The part is sent for further inspection to determine the cause of the defect\"], \"correct_answer\": \"C) The production for that hour is put on hold until the issue is resolved\", \"explanation\": \"When a defective part is found, the production for that hour is put on hold to prevent further defective parts from being produced, allowing for the issue to be investigated and resolved.\", \"module_index\": 1}, {\"question\": \"What information is typically included in the in-process inspection documentation?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) Only the part's dimensions and tolerances\", \"B) The machine used, work order number, item, and quantity\", \"C) The operator's name, production date, and shift\", \"D) The part's material, weight, and storage location\"], \"correct_answer\": \"B) The machine used, work order number, item, and quantity\", \"explanation\": \"The in-process inspection documentation typically includes detailed information about the part being produced, such as the machine used, work order number, item, and quantity, to ensure accurate tracking and verification.\", \"module_index\": 1}, {\"question\": \"What is the purpose of the 'hold card' in in-process inspection?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) To record the production schedule and deadlines\", \"B) To document the part's inspection results and defects\", \"C) To notify the production team of changes to the production schedule\", \"D) To track the inventory levels of raw materials and finished goods\"], \"correct_answer\": \"B) To document the part's inspection results and defects\", \"explanation\": \"The 'hold card' is used to document the inspection results and defects found during in-process inspection, allowing for the tracking and resolution of issues related to defective parts.\", \"module_index\": 1}, {\"question\": \"If a non-conformity is detected during the process, what is the immediate action taken on the affected material?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) Rework immediately\", \"B) Hold and inspect further\", \"C) Sort and mix with other materials\", \"D) Release with a warning\"], \"correct_answer\": \"B) Hold and inspect further\", \"explanation\": \"When a non-conformity is detected, the process is put on hold, and the material is inspected further to determine the cause and extent of the non-conformity.\", \"module_index\": 2}, {\"question\": \"What is the primary reason for holding material during the process?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) To meet production deadlines\", \"B) To inspect for non-conformities\", \"C) To sort and mix with other materials\", \"D) To reduce material waste\"], \"correct_answer\": \"B) To inspect for non-conformities\", \"explanation\": \"The primary reason for holding material is to inspect for non-conformities, such as defects or deviations from specifications, to ensure that only conforming material is released.\", \"module_index\": 2}, {\"question\": \"If a material is found to be out of specification during inspection, what is the likely next step?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) Release with a warning\", \"B) Rework to bring it within specification\", \"C) Sort and mix with other non-conforming materials\", \"D) Scrap the material\"], \"correct_answer\": \"B) Rework to bring it within specification\", \"explanation\": \"If a material is found to be out of specification, the likely next step is to rework it to bring it within specification, rather than releasing it or scrapping it.\", \"module_index\": 2}, {\"question\": \"What is the purpose of defining a process inspection point, such as checking the length of a material?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) To reduce production time\", \"B) To increase material yield\", \"C) To ensure conformance to customer specifications\", \"D) To improve process efficiency\"], \"correct_answer\": \"C) To ensure conformance to customer specifications\", \"explanation\": \"The purpose of defining a process inspection point is to ensure that the material meets the customer's specifications, such as length or other critical dimensions.\", \"module_index\": 2}, {\"question\": \"After segregation, if 1920 pieces are left out of 2000, what is the most likely reason for the reduction in the number of pieces?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) Defective pieces were removed due to dimensional errors\", \"B) Pieces were removed due to cosmetic defects\", \"C) Pieces were removed due to functional failures\", \"D) Pieces were removed due to material defects\"], \"correct_answer\": \"A) Defective pieces were removed due to dimensional errors\", \"explanation\": \"The reduction in the number of pieces after segregation is most likely due to the removal of defective pieces, and dimensional errors are a common reason for rejection.\", \"module_index\": 3}, {\"question\": \"What information is typically included on a scrap tag for a rejected part?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) Item number, customer name, and date of manufacture\", \"B) Item number, work order number, and batch number\", \"C) Item number, customer name, and reason for rejection\", \"D) Item number, work order number, and date of inspection\"], \"correct_answer\": \"B) Item number, work order number, and batch number\", \"explanation\": \"The scrap tag typically includes information that identifies the part and the production batch, such as the item number, work order number, and batch number.\", \"module_index\": 3}, {\"question\": \"What is the purpose of creating a scrap note for a rejected part?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) To document the reason for rejection and facilitate rework\", \"B) To document the reason for rejection and facilitate scrap disposal\", \"C) To document the inspection results and facilitate packaging\", \"D) To document the production schedule and facilitate shipping\"], \"correct_answer\": \"B) To document the reason for rejection and facilitate scrap disposal\", \"explanation\": \"The scrap note is created to document the reason for rejection and to facilitate the disposal of the rejected part as scrap.\", \"module_index\": 3}, {\"question\": \"What happens to a rejected part after it is tagged and documented?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) It is returned to the production line for rework\", \"B) It is stored in a designated scrap area for disposal\", \"C) It is shipped to the customer for repair\", \"D) It is used as a spare part for future repairs\"], \"correct_answer\": \"B) It is stored in a designated scrap area for disposal\", \"explanation\": \"The rejected part is typically stored in a designated scrap area after it is tagged and documented, where it will be disposed of according to the company's scrap disposal procedures.\", \"module_index\": 3}]",
    "is_processing": false
  },
