  {
    "id": 29,
    "title": "Work order, QA document and Rejection Reporting",
    "description": "Work order, QA document and Rejection Reporting",
    "video_url": "http://localhost:8000/static/videos/8e1e30fa-96ca-409b-8cc6-164884436618.mp4",
    "created_by_id": 1,
    "objectives": "## Objectives\n- Understand the process of creating a work order based on customer drawings and specifications\n- Learn how to identify and record key parameters such as metal type, wire diameter, ID, number of turns, and length in the work order\n- Familiarize with the in-process inspection procedure, including verification of dimensions and detection of non-conformities at regular intervals (e.g., every 2 hours)\n- Understand the process of holding and segregating non-conforming products, including the use of hold cards and recording of defects\n- Learn how to document and track non-conformities, including root cause analysis and corrective actions, to ensure quality control and customer satisfaction",
    "applications": "## Definitions\n- **Work Order**: A document that outlines the specifications and requirements for a particular job or project, based on the customer's drawing and specifications.\n- **Customer Specification**: The requirements and parameters specified by the customer for a particular product or job, including dimensions, materials, and other relevant details.\n- **In-Process Inspection**: The process of inspecting and verifying the product or job at various stages of production to ensure that it meets the required specifications and quality standards.\n- **Process Specification**: A document that outlines the specific processes and procedures to be followed during production, including the parameters and tolerances for each process.\n- **Hold Card**: A document used to identify and track products or materials that do not meet the required specifications or quality standards, and are therefore put on hold for further inspection or corrective action.\n- **Non-Conformity**: A deviation from the specified requirements or quality standards, which may result in the product or material being put on hold or rejected.\n\n## Practical Application\n- Creating a work order based on the customer's drawing and specifications, including all relevant parameters and dimensions.\n- Conducting in-process inspections at regular intervals (e.g. every 2 hours) to verify that the product meets the required specifications and quality standards.\n- Using a process specification document to guide the production process and ensure that all parameters and tolerances are met.\n- Utilizing a hold card system to identify and track non-conforming products or materials, and to initiate corrective action.\n- Implementing a quality control process that includes regular inspections, testing, and verification to ensure that the final product meets the required specifications and quality standards.\n- Maintaining accurate records and documentation of the production process, including inspection results, hold cards, and corrective actions taken.\n- Ensuring that all products or materials that do not meet the required specifications or quality standards are properly identified, tracked, and disposed of (e.g. through scrap or rework).",
    "quiz_data": "[{\"question\": \"What is the primary purpose of including customer specifications in a work order?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) To provide a general guideline for production\", \"B) To ensure operator safety during the manufacturing process\", \"C) To guarantee that the final product meets the customer's exact requirements\", \"D) To facilitate communication between production teams\"], \"correct_answer\": \"C) To guarantee that the final product meets the customer's exact requirements\", \"explanation\": \"Including customer specifications in a work order ensures that the production team has a clear understanding of the requirements and can manufacture the product accordingly.\", \"module_index\": 0}, {\"question\": \"Which of the following parameters is MOST likely to be included in a work order based on a customer's drawing?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) Material composition and machine setup instructions\", \"B) Operator training schedule and production timeline\", \"C) Number of turns, length, and wire dye specifications\", \"D) Quality control procedures and packaging requirements\"], \"correct_answer\": \"C) Number of turns, length, and wire dye specifications\", \"explanation\": \"The parameters mentioned in the work order are typically those that are critical to the production process and are directly related to the customer's specifications.\", \"module_index\": 0}, {\"question\": \"What is the primary benefit of releasing a work order to production after it has been prepared?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) To allow for changes to the customer's specifications\", \"B) To initiate the quality control process\", \"C) To enable the production team to set up their machines and manufacture the product according to the customer's specifications\", \"D) To facilitate communication between the production and quality control teams\"], \"correct_answer\": \"C) To enable the production team to set up their machines and manufacture the product according to the customer's specifications\", \"explanation\": \"Releasing a work order to production allows the production team to set up their machines and manufacture the product according to the customer's specifications, ensuring that the final product meets the required standards.\", \"module_index\": 0}, {\"question\": \"What is the relationship between a work order and the production process?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) A work order is generated after the production process is complete\", \"B) A work order is used to initiate the quality control process\", \"C) A work order provides a detailed guide for the production process, ensuring that the customer's specifications are met\", \"D) A work order is used to track inventory levels and manage supply chains\"], \"correct_answer\": \"C) A work order provides a detailed guide for the production process, ensuring that the customer's specifications are met\", \"explanation\": \"A work order provides a detailed guide for the production process, outlining the customer's specifications and requirements, and ensuring that the final product meets the required standards.\", \"module_index\": 0}, {\"question\": \"What is the primary purpose of in-process inspection and dimension validation in a manufacturing process?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) To verify the final product dimensions against customer specifications\", \"B) To monitor and control the production process to ensure adherence to process specifications\", \"C) To conduct a final quality check before product shipment\", \"D) To validate the design specifications against the manufacturing process capabilities\"], \"correct_answer\": \"B) To monitor and control the production process to ensure adherence to process specifications\", \"explanation\": \"In-process inspection and dimension validation are crucial to ensure that the manufacturing process is within specified limits, thereby guaranteeing the quality of the final product.\", \"module_index\": 1}, {\"question\": \"What is the significance of setting inner and outer diameter specifications, such as 12.22 to 12.38, in the manufacturing process?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) It ensures the product's aesthetic appeal and marketability\", \"B) It guarantees the product's functionality and performance within specified tolerances\", \"C) It determines the raw material selection and procurement process\", \"D) It influences the packaging and shipping logistics\"], \"correct_answer\": \"B) It guarantees the product's functionality and performance within specified tolerances\", \"explanation\": \"Setting precise specifications for inner and outer diameters is critical to ensure the product functions as intended and meets customer requirements, highlighting the importance of dimension validation.\", \"module_index\": 1}, {\"question\": \"At what stage of the manufacturing process does in-process inspection typically commence?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) After the final product assembly and quality check\", \"B) During the production process, after initial sampling and dimension validation\", \"C) Before the manufacturing process begins, as part of the design validation\", \"D) Concurrently with the customer specification review and approval\"], \"correct_answer\": \"B) During the production process, after initial sampling and dimension validation\", \"explanation\": \"In-process inspection starts after the initial sampling and dimension validation, ensuring that the production process stays within specified limits and that the final product meets quality standards.\", \"module_index\": 1}, {\"question\": \"What is the relationship between process specifications and the final product dimensions in terms of tolerances such as +0.15 and -0.7?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) Process specifications are less stringent than final product dimensions\", \"B) Process specifications dictate the final product dimensions, including tolerances\", \"C) Final product dimensions are independent of process specifications and tolerances\", \"D) Process specifications and final product dimensions have inverse relationships with tolerances\"], \"correct_answer\": \"B) Process specifications dictate the final product dimensions, including tolerances\", \"explanation\": \"Process specifications, including tolerances like +0.15 and -0.7, directly influence the final product dimensions, ensuring that the manufactured product meets both process and customer specifications.\", \"module_index\": 1}, {\"question\": \"What happens to a material that is found to be out of aspect during the process inspection, with a length of 31.6mm, when the specified length is between 30.8mm and 31.6mm?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) It is accepted and moved to the next stage of production\", \"B) It is put on hold for further evaluation\", \"C) It is immediately scrapped\", \"D) It is sent back to the previous stage for rework\"], \"correct_answer\": \"B) It is put on hold for further evaluation\", \"explanation\": \"The material is put on hold because its length is outside the specified range, and it needs to be evaluated further to determine the course of action.\", \"module_index\": 2}, {\"question\": \"If a batch of 2000 pieces is held due to being out of aspect, and after segregation, 1920 pieces are found to be within the acceptable range, what happens to the remaining pieces?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) They are automatically scrapped\", \"B) They are sent for rework\", \"C) They are put on hold for further evaluation\", \"D) They are added to the next batch for production\"], \"correct_answer\": \"C) They are put on hold for further evaluation\", \"explanation\": \"The remaining pieces are put on hold for further evaluation to determine the cause of the defect and the necessary course of action.\", \"module_index\": 2}, {\"question\": \"What is the purpose of recording the reason for rejection and the details of the rejected material in the rejection report?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) To track the number of rejected pieces\", \"B) To identify the cause of the defect and prevent future occurrences\", \"C) To determine the cost of the rejected material\", \"D) To assign blame to the production team\"], \"correct_answer\": \"B) To identify the cause of the defect and prevent future occurrences\", \"explanation\": \"The purpose of recording the reason for rejection and the details of the rejected material is to identify the cause of the defect and take corrective action to prevent future occurrences.\", \"module_index\": 2}, {\"question\": \"If a material is found to be out of aspect during the process inspection, and the length is 30.7mm, when the specified length is between 30.8mm and 31.6mm, what action is taken?\", \"type\": \"mcq\", \"options\": [\"A) The material is accepted and moved to the next stage of production\", \"B) The material is put on hold for further evaluation\", \"C) The material is immediately scrapped\", \"D) The material is sent back to the previous stage for rework\"], \"correct_answer\": \"B) The material is put on hold for further evaluation\", \"explanation\": \"The material is put on hold because its length is outside the specified range, and it needs to be evaluated further to determine the course of action.\", \"module_index\": 2}]",
