  {
    "id": 7,
    "module_id": 10,
    "order_index": 2,
    "title": "Process of Meeting Customer Specifications and Dimension Validation",
    "content": "## Process of Meeting Customer Specifications and Dimension Validation\n### Overview\nThe process involves validating product dimensions against customer specifications during production.\n\n### Key Steps\n* **In-Process Dimensions**: \n  - Inner Diameter (ID): 12.22 - 12.38 mm\n  - Outer Diameter (OD): As per gauge\n  - Free Length: 29.8 - 31.9 mm\n  - Number of Turns: As specified\n  - Direction: Right-Hand (RH)\n  - Coil Closed at Both Ends\n\n* **In-Process Inspection**:\n  - Conducted at regular intervals (e.g., every 2 hours)\n  - Quality Inspector verifies parts against specifications\n  - Records details: machine, workpiece number, item, quantity, size, and specification\n\n* **Non-Conformance Handling**:\n  - Parts not meeting specifications are held\n  - Reworked in a separate section\n  - Reasons for non-conformance documented (e.g., OD too large)\n\n* **Documentation**:\n  - Work Order Form with product specifications\n  - In-Process Inspection records\n  - Rejection Reporting for non-conforming parts\n\n### Critical Parameters\n* Inner Diameter (ID)\n* Outer Diameter (OD)\n* Free Length\n* Number of Turns\n* Direction\n* Coil Closure\n\n### Importance of Dimension Validation\nEnsures that the final product meets customer specifications, reducing the risk of rework or rejection.",
    "media_url": "http://localhost:8000/static/courses/10/2_Process_of_Meeting_Customer_Specifications_and_Dimension_Validation.mp4",
    "step_type": "instruction"
  },
  {
    "id": 8,
    "module_id": 10,
    "order_index": 3,
    "title": "Non-Conformity and Rejection Reporting",
    "content": "## Non-Conformity and Rejection Reporting\n### Overview\nThe module covers the process of handling non-conforming products and rejection reporting in a manufacturing setting.\n\n### Key Concepts\n* **In-Process Inspection**: Regular checks during production to ensure quality standards are met.\n* **Non-Conformity**: Products that do not meet specified requirements or customer drawings.\n* **Rejection Reporting**: Documentation of non-conforming products and the reasons for rejection.\n\n### Steps for Rejection Reporting\n1. **Identification of Non-Conformity**: Inspect products during production to identify deviations from specifications.\n2. **Documentation**: Record details of non-conforming products, including:\n\t* Item description\n\t* Work order number\n\t* Quantity\n\t* Date\n\t* Customer information\n\t* Reason for rejection\n3. **Segregation**: Separate non-conforming products from conforming ones.\n4. **Tagging**: Attach a \"Rejected\" tag to non-conforming products, including:\n\t* Item details\n\t* Reason for rejection\n\t* Inspector's signature\n5. **Reporting**: Document the rejection in the quality control report.\n\n### Example\n* A product with a length of 31.6 mm is outside the specified range (30.8-31.6 mm).\n* The product is tagged as \"Rejected\" and documented in the quality control report.\n\n### Importance\n* Ensures quality control and adherence to customer specifications.\n* Facilitates corrective actions to prevent future non-conformities.\n\n### Visual Aids\nThe provided video frames show:\n* A person documenting inspection results on a quality control report.\n* A \"Rejected\" tag being attached to a product.\n* A completed quality control report with a \"Rejected\" tag.",
    "media_url": "http://localhost:8000/static/courses/10/3_Non-Conformity_and_Rejection_Reporting.mp4",
    "step_type": "instruction"
  },
