  {
    "id": 14,
    "module_id": 12,
    "order_index": 2,
    "title": "Introduction to Dial Gauge and Parallelism Measurement",
    "content": "## Introduction to Dial Gauge and Parallelism Measurement\n### Overview\nThe dial gauge is a precision instrument used to measure small distances or displacements. It is commonly used to check the parallelism of surfaces.\n\n### Key Concepts\n* **Dial Gauge**: A precision measuring instrument used to measure small distances or displacements.\n* **Parallelism Measurement**: The process of checking if two surfaces are parallel to each other.\n* **Surface Plate**: A flat surface used as a reference for measurement.\n\n### Using a Dial Gauge for Parallelism Measurement\n1. **Setup**:\n\t* Place the workpiece on a surface plate.\n\t* Mount the dial gauge on a stable base.\n2. **Zeroing the Dial Gauge**:\n\t* Bring the dial gauge into contact with the workpiece.\n\t* Zero the dial gauge by adjusting the bezel.\n3. **Measuring Parallelism**:\n\t* Slowly rotate the workpiece while keeping the dial gauge in contact with it.\n\t* Observe the dial gauge reading to check for parallelism.\n\n### Interpreting Dial Gauge Readings\n* **Understanding the dial gauge scale**:\n\t+ 0 to 10 on the scale corresponds to 0.1 mm.\n\t+ 10 to 20 on the scale corresponds to 0.2 mm, and so on.\n* **Example**: A reading of 0.4 mm indicates that the surface is not more than 0.5 mm out of parallel, which is within the acceptable limit.\n\n### Best Practices\n* Ensure the dial gauge is properly zeroed before measurement.\n* Use a stable and flat surface plate as a reference.\n* Rotate the workpiece slowly and smoothly to avoid damaging the dial gauge or workpiece.\n\n### Summary\nThe dial gauge is a useful tool for measuring parallelism. By following the correct procedure and understanding the dial gauge readings, you can accurately check if two surfaces are parallel to each other.",
    "media_url": "http://localhost:8000/static/courses/12/2_Introduction_to_Dial_Gauge_and_Parallelism_Measurement.mp4",
    "step_type": "instruction"
  },
  {
    "id": 15,
    "module_id": 12,
    "order_index": 3,
    "title": "Number of Turns Measurement and Direction",
    "content": "## Number of Turns Measurement and Direction\n### Overview\nThe number of turns measurement is a critical parameter in evaluating the characteristics of springs.\n\n### Key Concepts\n* **Number of Turns**: The total number of times a spring is coiled around its axis.\n* **Measurement Procedure**:\n  * Start from any point on the spring.\n  * Rotate the spring by 360 degrees to complete one turn.\n  * Count the total number of turns.\n* **Direction**:\n  * **Clockwise**: The direction in which the spring is wound in a clockwise direction.\n  * **Anti-Clockwise**: The direction in which the spring is wound in an anti-clockwise direction.\n\n### Measurement Steps\n1. Hold the spring and identify the starting point.\n2. Rotate the spring by 360 degrees to complete one turn.\n3. Count the total number of turns.\n4. Record the direction of the spring (clockwise or anti-clockwise).\n\n### Example\n* A spring with 11.9 turns is considered to have approximately 12 turns.\n\n### Important Parameters\n* **Number of Turns**: A critical parameter in evaluating spring characteristics.\n* **Direction**: The direction of the spring winding (clockwise or anti-clockwise).\n\n### Additional Parameters to be Checked\n* **Spring Rate**: To be checked using a load testing machine.\n* **Perpendicularity**: To be checked using a separate instrument.",
    "media_url": "http://localhost:8000/static/courses/12/3_Number_of_Turns_Measurement_and_Direction.mp4",
    "step_type": "instruction"
  },
  {
    "id": 16,
    "module_id": 14,
    "order_index": 1,
    "title": "Understanding Customer Specifications and In-Process Dimensions",
    "content": "## Understanding Customer Specifications and In-Process Dimensions\n### Overview\nThe process of understanding customer specifications and in-process dimensions is crucial in manufacturing. It involves setting up a First Part Approval (FPA) or Setting Approval process to ensure that the final product meets the customer's requirements.\n\n### Key Concepts\n* **In-Process Dimensions**: These are the dimensions of a product during the manufacturing process.\n* **Customer Specifications**: These are the requirements specified by the customer for the final product.\n* **First Part Approval (FPA)**: A process used to verify that the initial product meets the customer's specifications.\n* **Setting Approval**: A process used to approve the setup of the manufacturing process.\n\n### Steps Involved in FPA/Setting Approval\n1. **Sampling**: Initial samples are taken from the production line.\n2. **Measurement**: The samples are measured against the customer's specifications.\n3. **Analysis**: The measurements are analyzed to ensure they meet the required dimensions.\n4. **Approval**: If the measurements are satisfactory, the setup is approved.\n\n### Important Dimensions to be Measured\n* **Y-Daya**: Measured using a specific method (1.5 + 0.15, -0.12).\n* **ID (Inner Diameter)**: Customer specification is 12, while in-process sampling is set at 12.3.\n* **Length**: Measured using vernier calipers (e.g., 32.76, 32.99).\n* **Spring Rate**: Measured to ensure it meets customer specifications.\n* **Parallelism**: Checked to ensure it is within the allowed tolerance.\n* **Perpendicularity**: Verified to meet customer requirements.\n\n### Tools Used\n* **Vernier Calipers**: Used to measure dimensions such as length and diameter.\n\n### Process Flow\n1. Initial sampling and measurement.\n2. Analysis of measurements against customer specifications.\n3. Approval of the setup if measurements are satisfactory.\n4. Continuation of production with approved setup.\n\nBy following this process, manufacturers can ensure that their products meet customer specifications and are produced with the correct in-process dimensions.",
    "media_url": "http://localhost:8000/static/courses/14/1_Understanding_Customer_Specifications_and_In-Process_Dimensions.mp4",
    "step_type": "instruction"
  },
  {
    "id": 17,
    "module_id": 14,
    "order_index": 2,
    "title": "Final Dimension Checking and Customer Specification Verification",
    "content": "## Final Dimension Checking and Customer Specification Verification\n### Overview\nThe final step in the manufacturing process involves verifying that the product meets the customer's specifications. This is done by checking the final dimensions of the product.\n\n### Key Concepts\n* **Final Dimension Checking**: Verifying the product's dimensions after completing all manufacturing processes.\n* **Customer Specification Verification**: Ensuring the product meets the customer's required specifications.\n\n### Step-by-Step Process\n1. **Check Final Dimensions**: Measure the product's dimensions using appropriate tools (e.g., Vernier caliper, height gauge).\n2. **Compare with Specifications**: Compare the measured dimensions with the customer's specifications.\n3. **Verify Compliance**: Ensure the product meets the required specifications.\n\n### Tools Used\n* Vernier caliper\n* Height gauge\n\n### Example Verification\n* Measured dimension: 11.98, 12.02, 12.03\n* Customer specification: 12 +/- 0.15\n* Verification: The measured dimensions are within the specified range.\n\n### Importance\n* Ensures the product meets customer requirements.\n* Prevents defective products from being shipped.\n* Maintains quality control and customer satisfaction.\n\n### Best Practices\n* Use calibrated measuring tools.\n* Follow standard operating procedures (SOPs) for measurement.\n* Document all measurements and verification results.",
    "media_url": "http://localhost:8000/static/courses/14/2_Final_Dimension_Checking_and_Customer_Specification_Verification.mp4",
    "step_type": "instruction"
  },
