    "order_index": 1,
    "title": "Work Order Preparation and Customer Drawing",
    "content": "## Work Order Preparation and Customer Drawing\n### Overview\nThe work order is a crucial document that outlines the specifications and requirements for producing a product according to customer demands.\n\n### Key Components of a Work Order\n* **Customer Drawing**: The foundation for creating a work order, providing essential details about the product.\n* **Product Specifications**: Include parameters such as:\n\t+ Material to be used\n\t+ Wire diameter\n\t+ Inner diameter (ID)\n\t+ Number of turns\n\t+ Length\n\t+ Other relevant specifications\n\n### Work Order Preparation Process\n1. **Receiving Customer Drawing**: The process begins with receiving the customer's drawing.\n2. **Creating the Work Order**: The drawing is used as a base to create the work order, incorporating all necessary specifications.\n3. **Releasing to Production**: The completed work order is then released to the production team.\n4. **Machine Setup**: The operator uses the work order to set up the machine according to the specified requirements.\n\n### Importance of Work Order\n* Ensures that the product meets customer specifications.\n* Guides the production process to achieve the desired outcome.\n* Facilitates quality control by outlining critical parameters.\n\n### Example from the Transcript\nThe transcript highlights that the work order includes details such as the metal to be used, wire dye, ID, number of turns, and length, all of which are derived from the customer's drawing.",
    "media_url": "http://localhost:8000/static/courses/23/1_Work_Order_Preparation_and_Customer_Drawing.mp4",
    "step_type": "instruction"
  },
  {
    "id": 35,
    "module_id": 23,
    "order_index": 2,
    "title": "In-Process Inspection and Quality Control",
    "content": "## In-Process Inspection and Quality Control\n### Overview\n\nIn-process inspection is a critical step in ensuring the quality of products during manufacturing. It involves verifying that the product meets the specified requirements at various stages of production.\n\n### Key Concepts\n* **Work Order Form**: A document that outlines the product specifications, including dimensions, material, and other relevant details.\n* **In-Process Inspection Report**: A document used to record the inspection results, including measurements and observations.\n* **Sampling**: The process of selecting a representative sample from the production batch for inspection.\n* **Inspection Parameters**: The specific characteristics of the product that are measured and verified during inspection, such as:\n\t+ Inner diameter (ID)\n\t+ Outer diameter (OD)\n\t+ Free length\n\t+ Number of turns\n\t+ Direction\n\t+ Closed coil\n\n### In-Process Inspection Procedure\n1. **Sampling**: A sample is selected from the production batch.\n2. **Measurement**: The sample is measured against the specified parameters.\n3. **Verification**: The measurements are verified against the work order specifications.\n4. **Recording**: The inspection results are recorded on the in-process inspection report.\n5. **Frequency**: Inspections are performed at regular intervals (e.g., every 2 hours).\n\n### Importance of In-Process Inspection\n* Ensures that products meet the required specifications.\n* Detects defects or deviations early in the production process.\n* Prevents further processing of defective products.\n* Maintains quality control and reduces waste.\n\n### Quality Control\n* **Quality Inspector**: Responsible for verifying the product against the specifications.\n* **Rejection Reporting**: Documents any defects or deviations found during inspection.\n* **Corrective Action**: Takes corrective action to address any issues identified during inspection.",
    "media_url": "http://localhost:8000/static/courses/23/2_In-Process_Inspection_and_Quality_Control.mp4",
    "step_type": "instruction"
  },
  {
    "id": 36,
    "module_id": 23,
    "order_index": 3,
    "title": "Rejection Reporting and Scrap Management",
    "content": "## Rejection Reporting and Scrap Management\n### Overview\nThe process involves identifying and documenting defective products during in-process inspection.\n\n### Key Steps\n* **Inspection**: Products are inspected at regular intervals (e.g., every 2 hours) to check for defects.\n* **Defect Identification**: Defects are identified and recorded, including the type and quantity of defects.\n* **Rejection Reporting**: A rejection report is generated for defective products, including details such as:\n\t+ Item number\n\t+ Work order number\n\t+ Quantity\n\t+ Reason for rejection\n\t+ Customer information\n* **Scrap Management**: Defective products are tagged with a \"Rejected\" label and sent to the store for scrap reporting.\n\n### Important Details\n* In-process inspection reports are used to track product quality.\n* Defective products are segregated and counted.\n* Rejection reports are used to document and track defective products.\n* Scrap reporting is done to record and manage defective products.\n\n### Example\n* 2000 pieces were held due to defects.\n* After segregation, 1920 pieces were okay, and 80 pieces were rejected.\n* The rejected pieces were tagged with a \"Rejected\" label and sent to the store for scrap reporting.",
    "media_url": "http://localhost:8000/static/courses/23/3_Rejection_Reporting_and_Scrap_Management.mp4",
    "step_type": "instruction"
  },
  {
    "id": 42,
    "module_id": 25,
    "order_index": 1,
    "title": "Application and Control of Plug Gauge in Mass Production",
    "content": "## Application and Control of Plug Gauge in Mass Production\n### Overview\nThe plug gauge is a precision instrument used to measure the internal diameter (ID) of a component.\n\n### Key Concepts\n* **Plug Gauge Function**: Measures ID to ensure it meets specifications.\n* **Specifications**:\n\t+ In-process: 12.2 to 12.4 mm\n\t+ Final: 11.93 to 12.15 mm (customer specs: 12 +0.15, -0.07)\n* **Go/No-Go Principle**: Plug gauge has two ends:\n\t+ Go end: Should fit into the component.\n\t+ No-Go end: Should not fit into the component.\n\n### Application in Mass Production\n* Used for quick inspection of components during production.\n* Helps maintain quality control by ensuring components are within specified tolerances.\n* Operators and quality inspectors use plug gauges to verify component dimensions.\n\n### Benefits\n* Fast and efficient inspection process.\n* Ensures consistency in component dimensions.\n* Reduces the need for complex measuring instruments during production.\n\n### Control and Inspection\n* Regular calibration of plug gauges is essential.\n* Quality inspectors verify the dimensions of components using plug gauges.\n* Records of inspections are maintained, as shown in the setting variability chart.",
    "media_url": "http://localhost:8000/static/courses/25/1_Application_and_Control_of_Plug_Gauge_in_Mass_Production.mp4",
    "step_type": "instruction"
  },
  {
    "id": 43,
    "module_id": 26,
    "order_index": 1,
    "title": "Work Order Preparation and Customer Specifications",
    "content": "## Work Order Preparation and Customer Specifications\n### Overview\nA work order is a document that outlines the specifications and requirements for a particular job or task. It is prepared based on customer drawings and specifications.\n\n### Key Components of a Work Order\n* Customer drawing and specifications\n* Product details (e.g., material, wire diameter, inner diameter)\n* Critical parameters (e.g., length, pitch, spring rate)\n* Tolerances and limits\n\n### Preparation Process\n1. Receive customer drawing and specifications\n2. Create a work order based on the received specifications\n3. Include all relevant details, such as:\n\t* Material and wire diameter\n\t* Inner and outer diameter\n\t* Length and pitch\n\t* Spring rate and other critical parameters\n4. Specify tolerances and limits for each parameter\n\n### Importance of Customer Specifications\n* Ensures that the final product meets customer requirements\n* Guides the production process to produce the desired output\n* Helps to prevent errors and rework\n\n### Example from the Transcript\n* The work order form includes details such as:\n\t+ Wire diameter: 1.40 mm\n\t+ Inner diameter: 12.00 mm\n\t+ Length: 30.50 mm\n\t+ Spring rate: 0.180 kg/mm\n* The form also includes tolerances and limits for each parameter, such as:\n\t+ Inner diameter: 12.22 - 12.38 mm\n\n### In-Process Dimensions\n* The work order includes in-process dimensions, such as:\n\t+ Inner diameter: 12.22 - 12.38 mm\n\t+ Outer diameter: >15.02 - <15.18 mm\n\t+ Free length: >32.60 - <32.10 mm\n\nBy following this process, a work order is created that accurately reflects the customer's specifications and guides the production process to produce a high-quality product.",
    "media_url": "http://localhost:8000/static/courses/26/1_Work_Order_Preparation_and_Customer_Specifications.mp4",
    "step_type": "instruction"
  },
  {
    "id": 44,
    "module_id": 26,
    "order_index": 2,
    "title": "In-Process Inspection and Quality Control",
    "content": "## In-Process Inspection and Quality Control\n### Overview\nIn-process inspection is a critical quality control process that ensures products meet specifications during manufacturing.\n\n### Key Components of In-Process Inspection\n* **In-Process Inspection Report**: A document that records the inspection results at regular intervals (e.g., every 2 hours).\n* **Specifications**: Details the acceptable limits for product dimensions, such as:\n\t+ Inner diameter (ID)\n\t+ Outer diameter (OD)\n\t+ Length\n\t+ Other critical parameters\n* **Inspection Frequency**: Regular checks are performed at fixed intervals (e.g., 10 am, 12 pm, 2 pm, 4 pm, 6 pm).\n\n### Process Flow\n1. **Production**: The product is manufactured according to the work order and specifications.\n2. **In-Process Inspection**: The Quality Inspector checks the product at regular intervals.\n3. **Verification**: The inspector verifies the product dimensions against the specified limits.\n4. **Hold/Release**: If the product is non-conforming, it is held, and the production is stopped. The inspector records the defect and takes corrective action.\n\n### Corrective Action\n* **Hold Card**: A card is attached to the non-conforming product to indicate that it is on hold.\n* **Corrective Action**: The inspector records the defect, and the production team takes corrective action to rectify the issue.\n* **100% Inspection**: In some cases, a 100% inspection may be required to ensure that all products meet the specifications.\n\n### Importance of In-Process Inspection\n* Ensures product quality and reliability\n* Prevents defects and reduces waste\n* Facilitates early detection and correction of issues\n* Enhances customer satisfaction and loyalty",
    "media_url": "http://localhost:8000/static/courses/26/2_In-Process_Inspection_and_Quality_Control.mp4",
    "step_type": "instruction"
  },
  {
    "id": 45,
    "module_id": 26,
    "order_index": 3,
    "title": "Process Completion, Non-Conformity, and Rework",
    "content": "## Process Completion, Non-Conformity, and Rework\n### Overview\nThe process is considered complete when the product meets the required specifications. However, if a non-conformity is detected, the product is put on hold and sent for rework.\n\n### Key Concepts\n* **Process Completion**: The process is complete when the product meets the required specifications.\n* **Non-Conformity**: A product that does not meet the required specifications is considered non-conforming.\n* **Rework**: The process of correcting non-conformities to bring the product up to the required specifications.\n\n### Reasons for Non-Conformity\n* **OD (Outside Diameter)**: Non-conformity due to incorrect outside diameter.\n* **Length**: Non-conformity due to incorrect length.\n* **Aspect**: Non-conformity due to issues with the product's aspect (e.g., visual inspection).\n* **Material Mix**: Non-conformity due to incorrect material mix.\n\n### In-Process Inspection\n* The in-process inspection report is used to track and record the inspection results.\n* The report includes details such as:\n\t+ Item being inspected\n\t+ Specifications\n\t+ Inspection results\n\t+ Remarks\n\n### Rework Process\n* The rework process involves correcting the non-conformities identified during inspection.\n* The product is then re-inspected to ensure it meets the required specifications.\n\n### Example of Non-Conformity\n* 31 pieces held due to length being more than 30.\n* 72 pieces held due to out-of-aspect issues.\n* Material mix issues.\n\nBy following this structured approach, the module provides a concise overview of the key concepts related to process completion, non-conformity, and rework.",
    "media_url": "http://localhost:8000/static/courses/26/3_Process_Completion_Non-Conformity_and_Rework.mp4",
    "step_type": "instruction"
  },
  {
    "id": 46,
    "module_id": 26,
    "order_index": 4,
    "title": "Final Inspection, Segregation, and Scrap Disposal",
    "content": "## Final Inspection, Segregation, and Scrap Disposal\n### Overview\nThe process involves inspecting products, segregating them based on quality, and disposing of scrap.\n\n### Key Steps\n* **Inspection**: Products undergo a final inspection to check for defects or irregularities.\n* **Segregation**: Products are segregated into different categories based on their quality.\n* **Scrap Disposal**: Defective or non-conforming products are identified and tagged for disposal.\n\n### Tagging and Documentation\n* **Red Tag**: A red tag is attached to defective products, indicating they are not reworkable.\n* **Details to be filled**: \n  + Item name\n  + Code number\n  + Quantity\n  + Date\n  + Customer name\n  + Reason for rejection\n* **Inspector's Signature**: The inspector signs off on the rejection.\n\n### Process Flow\n1. Products are held after inspection (e.g., 2000 pieces).\n2. After segregation, the number of defective pieces is identified (e.g., 80 pieces rejected).\n3. Defective products are tagged with a red tag and sent to the store for scrap disposal.\n4. The tagged products are then disposed of as scrap.\n\n### Importance\nProper segregation and scrap disposal ensure that only quality products are shipped to customers, maintaining product integrity and customer satisfaction.",
    "media_url": "http://localhost:8000/static/courses/26/4_Final_Inspection_Segregation_and_Scrap_Disposal.mp4",
    "step_type": "instruction"
  },
  {
    "id": 47,
    "module_id": 29,
    "order_index": 1,
    "title": "Work Order Preparation and Customer Specifications",
    "content": "## Work Order Preparation and Customer Specifications\n### Overview\n* A work order is a document that outlines the specifications and requirements for a production process.\n* It is prepared based on customer drawings and specifications.\n\n### Key Components of a Work Order\n* Customer drawing parameters\n* Material specifications (e.g., metal, wire dye)\n* Product dimensions (e.g., length, ID, number of turns)\n* Other relevant specifications (e.g., spring rate, pitch)\n\n### Preparation Process\n1. Receive customer drawing\n2. Extract relevant parameters and specifications\n3. Create a work order document with the extracted information\n4. Release the work order to production\n\n### Purpose of a Work Order\n* Guides the production process\n* Ensures that the final product meets customer specifications\n* Enables the operator to set up the machine correctly\n\n### Key Takeaways\n* A work order is a critical document that ensures production meets customer requirements.\n* It contains detailed specifications and parameters extracted from customer drawings.\n* The work order guides the production process and ensures that the final product meets customer expectations.",
    "media_url": "http://localhost:8000/static/courses/29/1_Work_Order_Preparation_and_Customer_Specifications.mp4",
    "step_type": "instruction"
  },
  {
    "id": 48,
    "module_id": 29,
    "order_index": 2,
    "title": "In-Process Inspection and Dimension Validation",
    "content": "## In-Process Inspection and Dimension Validation\n### Overview\nThe module focuses on the importance of in-process inspection and dimension validation in ensuring product quality.\n\n### Key Concepts\n* **In-Process Inspection**: Regular checks during the manufacturing process to ensure dimensions meet specifications.\n* **Dimension Validation**: Verification of product dimensions against customer requirements.\n* **Specifications**: Defined limits for product dimensions, such as:\n\t+ Inner Diameter (ID)\n\t+ Outer Diameter (OD)\n\t+ Free Length\n\t+ Number of Turns\n\t+ Direction\n\t+ Closed Coil\n\n### Inspection Process\n1. **Sampling**: Random sampling of products at regular intervals (e.g., every 2 hours).\n2. **Verification**: Quality inspector checks sampled products against specifications.\n3. **Non-Conformance**: If a product fails to meet specifications, it is held and marked for review.\n\n### Documentation\n* **Work Order Form**: Outlines product specifications and requirements.\n* **In-Process Inspection Report**: Records inspection results and any non-conformities.\n* **Under Inspection Variation Report**: Documents variations detected during inspection.\n\n### Importance of In-Process Inspection\n* Ensures product quality and reduces waste.\n* Facilitates early detection of defects or variations.\n* Enables prompt corrective action to prevent further non-conformities.\n\n### Best Practices\n* Regularly review and update specifications and inspection procedures.\n* Train quality inspectors to ensure accurate and consistent inspections.\n* Maintain accurate records of inspection results and non-conformities.",
    "media_url": "http://localhost:8000/static/courses/29/2_In-Process_Inspection_and_Dimension_Validation.mp4",
    "step_type": "instruction"
  },
  {
    "id": 49,
    "module_id": 29,
    "order_index": 3,
    "title": "Rejection Reporting and Scrap Management",
    "content": "## Rejection Reporting and Scrap Management\n### Overview\nThe process involves identifying and managing rejected materials during production.\n\n### Key Steps\n* **In-Process Inspection**: \n  - Inspecting products at regular intervals (e.g., every 2 hours).\n  - Checking dimensions (e.g., length) against specified limits (e.g., 30.8 to 31.6).\n* **Identifying Rejected Material**: \n  - Material outside specified limits is held (e.g., length > 31.6 or < 30.8).\n* **Segregation**: \n  - Separating rejected material from acceptable products.\n  - Example: 2000 pieces held, after segregation, 1920 pieces identified as out of specification.\n* **Labeling Rejected Material**: \n  - Attaching a red tag to indicate non-reworkable items.\n  - Documenting reasons for rejection.\n* **Scrap Management**: \n  - Moving rejected material to a scrap area.\n  - Recording in scrap notes for inventory management.\n\n### Key Concepts\n* **In-Process Inspection Report**: A document used to record inspection results.\n* **Rejection Tagging**: Labeling rejected material for identification.\n* **Scrap Notes**: Documentation for tracking scrap material.\n\n### Best Practices\n* Regular inspections to catch defects early.\n* Accurate documentation of rejection reasons.\n* Efficient segregation and labeling of rejected material.",
    "media_url": "http://localhost:8000/static/courses/29/3_Rejection_Reporting_and_Scrap_Management.mp4",
    "step_type": "instruction"
  }
]


